Defendant Nathaniel R Smith in court with attorney Diane R Caspari.  Defendant Nathaniel R Smith in custody.  Erin M Karshen appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant.  Private PSI is reviewed.

The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 10 YEARS, consecutive, with credit for 0 days time served; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 5 YEARS; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 5 YEARS.  

Defendant is NOT eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program or the Earned Release Program. The defendant is not appropriate for the Substance Abuse Program.

Court costs, fees, surcharges and restitution be paid through collection by the department of Corrections from 25% of funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b) and as a condition of extended supervision.

Conditions of Extended Supervision:
- Complete 1000 hours of community service; 
- No further violations of the law rising to the level of probable cause; 
- Successfully complete a Batterers Intervention program;
- Mental health evaluation and take all prescribed medication; 
- Cognitive thinking intervention counseling;
- Attend parenting class; 
- AODA assessment and comply with any treatment;
- No use or possession of illegal drugs or drug paraphernalia; 
- Absolute sobriety with monthly random urine screens; 
- Attend treatment and counseling programs as determined by agent; 
- No contact with children under the age of 16 without consent of DOC; 
- No contact with the victim;
- Register and comply with the lifetime sex offender registry;
- Obtain/comply with sex offender treatment; 
- Seek/maintain employment;
- Obtain GED/HSED; 
- Provide DNA sample and pay surcharge; 
- Pay all supervision fees;
- Restitution set at ZERO;
- Pay all costs, surcharges, victim/witness surcharge and assessments by the end of extended supervision; any balance remaining unpaid at that time is to be converted to a civil judgment against the defendant;
- Pay child support, failure to pay child support will result in revocation.

Pursuant to Wisconsin Statutes section 973.176, the Court advised the defendant of the following restrictions:  Firearm possession; Voting and Child sex offender working with children.

Appellate rights notice given to the defendant. 

